\begin{align*}
\arcsin \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} &= \arcsin \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \\
&= \frac{\pi}{2} - \arccos \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \\
&= \frac{\pi}{2} - \arccos \left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{2}}\right) \\
&= \frac{\pi}{2} - \arccos \frac{1}{2}.
\end{align*}
To find $\arccos \frac{1}{2},$ we can use a calculator or table of values. We have $\arccos \frac{1}{2} \approx 1.10715.$ Therefore,
\begin{align*}
\arcsin \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} &= \frac{\pi}{2} - 1.10715 \\
&= 0.41825 \cdot \pi \approx 2.3562.
\end{align*}
Therefore, $\arcsin \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \approx 2.3562$ radians.The answer is : \frac{\pi}{4}.

